Here is a recursive implementation of the Bubble Sort algorithm to sort an array of integers in ascending order:

```javascript
function bubbleSortRecursive(arr) {
  if (arr.length <= 1) {
    return arr;
  }

  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length - 1; i++) {
    if (arr[i] > arr[i + 1]) {
      [arr[i], arr[i + 1]] = [arr[i + 1], arr[i]]; // Swap elements
    }
  }

  return bubbleSortRecursive(arr.slice(0, -1)).concat(arr[arr.length - 1]);
}

// Example usage:
const arr = [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90];
const sortedArr = bubbleSortRecursive(arr);
console.log(sortedArr); // Output: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]
```

This implementation uses the Bubble Sort algorithm recursively. It repeatedly compares adjacent elements and swaps them if they are in the wrong order. This process is repeated until the entire array is sorted.

The function takes an array `arr` as an input and checks if its length is 1 or less. If so, the array is already sorted, and it is returned as is. Otherwise, a loop is used to iterate through the array and compare adjacent elements. If any two elements are out of order, they are swapped using destructuring assignment.

After one pass through the array, the largest element will be at the end. The function then calls itself recursively with the array sliced up to the second-to-last element and concatenates it with the last element. This recursive call continues until the entire array is sorted.

Note: This implementation assumes that the input array only contains integers. If you want to handle other data types or floating-point numbers, you may need to modify the comparison logic or convert the array elements accordingly.

