```javascript
// Function to remove duplicates from a string
function removeDuplicates(str) {
  let result = "";
  for (let i = 0; i < str.length; i++) {
    if (result.indexOf(str[i]) === -1) {
      result += str[i];
    }
  }
  return result;
}

// Function to check if two strings are anagrams
function areAnagrams(str1, str2) {
  // Remove duplicates and convert to lowercase
  str1 = removeDuplicates(str1.toLowerCase().replace(/[^a-z]/g, ""));
  str2 = removeDuplicates(str2.toLowerCase().replace(/[^a-z]/g, ""));

  // Check if the lengths are different
  if (str1.length !== str2.length) {
    return false;
  }

  // Create a frequency counter object
  const frequencyCounter = {};

  // Count the frequency of characters in the first string
  for (let char of str1) {
    frequencyCounter[char] = (frequencyCounter[char] || 0) + 1;
  }

  // Decrement the frequency counter for characters in the second string
  for (let char of str2) {
    if (!frequencyCounter[char]) {
      return false;
    }
    frequencyCounter[char]--;
  }

  // Check if all frequencies are zero
  for (let key in frequencyCounter) {
    if (frequencyCounter[key] !== 0) {
      return false;
    }
  }

  return true;
}

// Testing the program
console.log(areAnagrams("listen", "silent")); // true
console.log(areAnagrams("Eleven plus two", "Twelve plus one")); // true
console.log(areAnagrams("Listen", "silent")); // true
console.log(areAnagrams("Astronomer", "Moon starer")); // true
console.log(areAnagrams("Hello", "World")); // false
```

The `removeDuplicates` function removes duplicates from a string by iterating through each character and only appending it to the result if it doesn't already exist.

The `areAnagrams` function first removes duplicates and converts both strings to lowercase. It also removes any non-alphabetic characters using a regular expression (`/[^a-z]/g`). Then, it checks if the lengths of the strings are different. If they are, they cannot be anagrams, so it returns `false`.

Next, it creates a frequency counter object to count the frequency of each character in the first string. It uses a `for...of` loop to iterate through each character and increments the frequency counter accordingly.

After that, it iterates through each character in the second string and checks if the character exists in the frequency counter object. If it doesn't, it means the characters are different, so it returns `false`. Otherwise, it decrements the frequency counter for that character.

Finally, it checks if all frequencies in the counter object are zero. If any frequency is non-zero, it means there are extra characters in one of the strings, so it returns `false`. If all frequencies are zero, it means the strings are anagrams, so it returns `true`.

The program has a time complexity of O(n), where n is the length of the input strings, as it iterates through the strings only once.

